Question (from GJP):

#1414 On 15 September 2014, will the Arctic sea ice extent be less than that of 15 September 2013?

Interpretaion Clarifications (from GJP):

The sea ice extent is the total surface area of the Arctic under ice cover; a lower sea ice extent makes shipping and fishing in the region more feasible. In recent years, mid-September has marked the point at which Arctic sea ice extent has decreased to its lowest point, after which the freeze begins again. On 15 September 2013, the Arctic sea ice extent was 4,834,931 square kilometers (km2). Outcome will be determined on 15 September 2014 by the Japan Aerospace Exploration Agencys Arctic Sea Ice Monitor, at http://www.ijis.iarc.uaf.edu/en/home/seaice_extent.htm . For historical trends, click data download and save as a csv file. If the resolution criteria are not met, GJP will assume the following as the status quo outcome: Arctic sea ice extent on 15 September 2014 will not be less than 4,834,931 square kilometers.

CHAMPS-KNOW Analysis

Comparison Classes (Base Rates):

The closest comparable base rate would likely be the number of times sea ice extent has been below the benchmark over the last decade. See Table One below for that information.

Other comparisons could involve examining the relationship between warming and sea ice extent, but that information should already be embodied in the sea ice extent data (see Whitneys theorem about embedding dimensions).

Hunt for Right Information:

Because the question will be decided by reporting from Japanese Aerospace Exploration Agency JAXA, their data will be primarily used in this analysis.

Data were available from two sources:

  • The arctic sea ice monitor page (here) which had data from 2003 until the present (8/22/2014)

  • Long term sea ice monitoring page (here) which required registration to access data from 1978 until 2013.

There were slight discrepancies between the data sets likely due to differences in calculating sea ice extent. To accomadate such discrepances, the historical dataset was paired with the more recent data set by combining data from 1978-2003 from the long term sea ice monitoring page with data from 2003-present from the arctic sea ice monitor page.

This analysis rests primarily on statistical projections using various techniques. A brief intro to ARIMAs can be found here and here. For information on state space reconstruction techniques, consult the work of [Floris Takens](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Takens'_theorem) and George Sugihara

Adjust and Update Information:

The models below can be updated on a weekly basis with more information from satellite data, but should be pretty robust to changes and should give a pretty good estimate even without new forthcoming data.

Modeling

The modeling approach is three-fold and consists of:

  • Visual inspection of trends in historical data

  • Autoregressive integrated moving average (ARIMA) models

  • Model-free state space reconstruction (SSR) techniques (namely simplex projection) that can perform better than model based techniques 1

All modeling was done in R (this document was written in RMarkDown - thanks RStudio!!) and can be found here

ARIMA Modeling

Autoregressive integrated moving average (ARIMA) models use a combination of moving average models which smooth over a given time span by averaging and autoregressive models which regress a time series against itself (with lags) to produce reasonably good forecasts (usually) of stationary time series.

Figure 3: Sea Ice Extent forecast with an autoregressive integrated moving average model ARIMA(3,1,1) selected using Bayesian information criteria. Black line denotes historical data. Blue line denotes forecast. Dark grey shading indicates 80% confidence intervals. Light grey shading indicates 95% confidence intervals. Green line indicates sea ice extent on September 15, 2013.

Simplex Projection

Simplex projection is a state space reconstruction technique that provides model free forecasts of time series. A great overview of simplex projection can be found here and a comparision with other forecasting methods can be found here.

The first step in simplex dimension is choosing the appropriate embedding dimension (that which produces the highest predictive power) by examining correlations between predictions of historical data and the historical data itself.

Figure 4: Selection of embedding dimension prior to simplex dimension. An embedding dimension of two produces the highest correlation between predictions and actual values.

Figure 5: Forecasts from Simplex Projection. Black line denotes historical data. Blue line indicates projected sea ice extent. Green line indicates sea ice extent on September 15, 2013.

Select the right level of effort.

Question is understandable, information is accessible, and personal background makes this intriguing (time series analysis is fun!).

Power players and preferences

Relevant players are humans and the japanese monitoring agency. Preferences should ideally not come into play as the outcome of the question is based on empirical data.

Norms, Rules, Protocols

It seems the only relevant norms, rules or protocols for this question revolve around reporting method and calculating sea ice extent. The agency has changed calculation methods in the past, but unless they change them again prior to the 15th, this facet should not have a large impact on the outcomes.

Other Perspectives

It seems most news sources (from a simple google search) cite warming trends, waves, etc as leading to record declines in sea ice extent, but few contain any data whatsoever. That being said, not one article (from a cursory search) seems to offer that this year could be anything other than a record low for sea ice extent.

Wildcards

Not likely, but then they never are

Forecast

This forecast is based almost entirely off of modeling.

Based on:

  • visual inspection of historical trends (6 out of the past 7 years have had sea ice extent less than (or at) the extent found on September 15, 2013)

  • ARIMA models (the projected value and ~ 70% of the confidence bands are below the benchmark)

  • Simplex projection (the projected value is less than the benchmark)

I am going to assign an initial 85% probability to the outcome that sea ice extent will be less than 4.8349 106km2 on September 15, 2014 to be updated (probably upward) in the coming weeks.
